      </tr>

      <tr>
        <td> 0245 - 0250 </td>
        <td> Debrief </td>
      </tr>
	  
      <tr>
        <td> 0250 - 0300 </td>
        <td> Departure </td>
      </tr>

    </tbody>
  </table>
  
  <br />
  <b>Further Guidance:</b><br />

  <ul>
      <li><b>Plan</b> a remote-controlled robot, with an aptitude for <b>moving supah-fast</b> with optional <b>weapon(s) to obstruct other racers</b></li>
      <li>Use <b>Trello</b> or a similar management technique to organise necessary component-building and programming tasks.</li>
      <li>Using the <b>agile development philosophy</b>, begin iteratively building and programming the robot components within your group</li>
      <li>Ensure the robot is programmed to be <b>user-controllable</b> from a distance</li>
      <li>Have a <b>human race</b> or maybe an <b>epic rock-paper scissors battle</b> to <b>decide who drives the robot</b> (or pehaps decide in session [x], such that you can build the robot before potentially being in a <b>passive aggressive war</b> with each other, rather than after)</li>
      <li>Prepare to <b>race the robots</b> along a pre-set track by session [x].</li>
  </ul> 
  
  <br />
  <b>Further Learning:</b><br />

  <ul>
      <li>Read <b><a href="http://www.trustedreviews.com/opinion/best-top-robot-wars-robots-2939336">7 Coolest Robot Wars robots by Joe Roberts</a></b> for inspiration in gratuitous robotic violence.</li>
      <li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=meow">Watch cat videos</a> to relax and calm down after a stressful robot-buliding day</a></li>
  </ul>

  <b>Resources:</b>

